WORKFORCE "SKILLED LABOR"

Workforce (goal)
Skilled Labor (goal)

Usage:  workforce [chore] [on | off | <limit>] [island name | all]
        workforce no-work
        workforce where [chore | here]
        workforce why [chore | location | here]
        workforce copy <island name>
        workforce keep [number | all] <item name>
        workforce keep default [number | all | none]
        workforce limit [amount | none] [keywords]
        workforce nearby

Once your empire has purchased the Workforce progress reward, the empire's
citizens (NPCs) will start performing simple tasks for the empire. You can
enable or disable each specific task using the "workforce" command. The work-
force is generally much slower than a player would be at the same task. Most
workforce chores consume food from your empire's inventory. Food is collected
once per game day.

Typing "workforce" without a "type" after it will show you which workforce
chores are currently enabled for the island you're currently on. Chores with
asterisks have different settings on other islands. Empire leaders can set the
minimum rank to change the workforce settings.

The workforce is made up of the empire's citizens (NPCs). These citizens will
only work within 20 map tiles of their own homes, and must be on the same 
island. Citizens will only work on claimed land. Only one citizen will perform
a particular chore at each chore location at one time (build more chore
buildings to increase chore speed).

If you set your own limit on a chore, the empire won't produce more than that
limit on each island. Not all chores use the numeric limit (for example, the
abandon-* toggles don't use the limit).

You can use the "workforce copy" command to copy the workforce limit
configuration of another island into the island you are currently in. Using
"workforce keep" lets you prevent some or all of the item from being used.

Note: Your workforce will only produce resources up to your workforce cap.

See &cHELP WORKFORCE CHORES&0 for a list of all workforce chores with descriptions.
See &cHELP WORKFORCE LIMIT&0 for information on limiting production

See also: WORKFORCE CHORES, WORKFORCE WHERE, WORKFORCE WHY, NO-WORK,
          WORKFORCE KEEP, WORKFORCE CAP, WORKFORCE LIMIT, FEEDING WORKFORCE,
          WORKFORCE NEARBY
#
"WORKFORCE CAP"

Workforce will only gather resources up to a certain limit. Workers will not
work chores that would give you more of an item than that cap. You can see your
current workforce cap on your empire detail page.

You can set your own caps on chores by choosing a limit with the 'workforce'
command.

The maximum workforce cap is 100 per member, plus any additional amount earned
from progression goals. This is a global cap, but workers on each of your
islands will produce up to 25 of something, even if you're above the global
cap.

The workforce cap does not apply to dismantling buildings -- workers can still
dismantle and store the resources.

See also: WORKFORCE
#
"WORKFORCE CHORES" "WORKFORCE TYPES"

Workforce types:
  &yabandon-chopped:&0 NPCs will abandon a tile when they finish chopping it,
     or after burning it if burn-stumps is also on.
  &yabandon-dismantled:&0 NPCs will abandon a tile when they finish dismantling.
  &yabandon-farmed:&0 NPCs will abandon a tile when they finish farming.
  &ybuilding:&0 NPCs will build any building that has been started, or dismantle
            any building you've started to dismantle. They build using stored
            empire resources, not items on the ground. Workers can't provide
            coins, liquids (like water), or pools (like mana) for building. Any
            building that requires one of these must be finished manually. They
            will also build or dismantle vehicles.
  &yburn-stumps:&0 Will burn down 'stumps' tiles.
  &ychopping:&0 NPCs will chop down forests and desert groves (Not orchards - 
     use farming without replanting for that).
  &ycrafting:&0 NPCs will make certain crafts (see WORKFORCE CRAFTING).
  &ydismantle-mines:&0 marks empty mines to be dismantled by the building chore.
  &yfarming:&0 NPCs will harvest crops. Costs no food.
  &yfire-brigade:&0 NPCs will put out fires.
  &yfishing:&0 Will catch fish at the fishery. Costs no food.
  &ymaintenance:&0 NPCs will keep buildings and vehicles maintained.
  &ymilling:&0 Will mill grains into flour.
  &ymining:&0 NPCs will mine your mines.
  &cminting (skilled):&0 NPCs will mint treasure into coins.
  &yoilmaking:&0 Will press oil.
  &yproduction:&0 NPCs will produce resources at various buildings.
  &yreplanting:&0 after farming crops, NPCs will replant them.
  &ysawing:&0 NPCs will convert trees into lumber at lumber yards.
  &yscraping:&0 NPCs will convert trees into logs at lumber yards.
  &yshearing:&0 NPCs will shear animals in stables.
  &ysmelting:&0 NPCs will smelt ore and precious metals at foundries.
  &ytanning:&0 NPCs will tan skins into leather.
  &yweaving:&0 NPCs will convert cotton to cloth at the tailor.
  
Items marked (skilled) require the Skilled Labor goal. Skilled Labor chores
tend to cost more food.

Additional workforce chores are available from progress buys:
  &gprospecting (Prospector Training):&0 NPCs will slowly prospect mountain tiles.

See also: ABANDON, WORKFORCE, FEEDING WORKFORCE
#
"WORKFORCE CRAFTING" "WORKFORCE CRAFTS"

The 'crafting' chore instructs your workforce to produce certain items. If you
want to use this chore, but turn off specific items, use 'workforce limit' on
those items.

Common things produced by this:
 Baker: village foods (gruel, pickled vegetables, bread)
 Forge: nails
 Potter: bricks
 Glass blower: glass ingots
 Tavern: barrels of ale

See also: WORKFORCE CHORES, WORKFORCE LIMIT
#
"WORKFORCE FOOD" "FEEDING WORKFORCE" "WORKFORCE EATING" "STARVING WORKFORCE" "WORKFORCE IS STARVING"

Once your empire has unlocked Workforce, your citizens will start doing work in
exchange for food. This food is collected once per day. If you don't have
enough, your workers on that island will begin to starve.

Starving citizens will no longer work, except for certain food-gathering chores
like farming and fishing. This work stoppage lasts at least a day, until the
normal time when food would be collected again. After that, if there's enough
food, they will resume their work.

Food for workers is always take from empire inventory on the island where they
are working. Each hour a citizen works requires 1 "hour of fullness" -- the
amount you see when you identify a piece of food. For example, if the food only
fills for 1 hour, 10 working citizens will eat 10 of it in an hour; but if it
fills for 24 hours instead, it will feed 24 citizens that hour.

Citizens will consume foods you have the most of first -- the same sorting you
see on the einventory command. It will use at most 100 of each type of food in
each hour, in order to avoid using up all of a single food.

Crops and fisheries are a good way to keep your workers fed. Diverse crops will
reduce the chances of running out of food. Not all crops can be eaten raw. Give
your workers a bakery and enable workforce crafting; they will cook raw foods
into additional things to eat.

See also: BAKERY, EINVENTORY, WORKFORCE, WORKFORCE CRAFTS, WORKFORCE WHY
#
"WORKFORCE KEEP" "WORKFORCE KEEP DEFAULT" "DEFAULT KEEP" "DEFAULT WORKFORCE KEEP"

Usage:  workforce keep
        workforce keep [number | all] <item name>
        workforce keep default [number | all | none]

This command will prevent your workers from using/eating an item in your
empire's inventory. You can specify more than one keyword if you're having
trouble targeting the right item.

This command only affects the island you are currently on. Using this command
with no argument will show current keep settings for the island; you can also
see keep settings on the einventory command. When typed with an item name but
no number/all argument, this command will toggle 'keep' on or off.

You can use 'workforce keep default' to set a default number to keep for any
new items your empire acquires.

Examples:
 > workforce keep stick
 > workforce keep all gold bar
 > workforce keep 200 spruce lumber
 > workforce keep default 1

See also: WORKFORCE, WORKFORCE LIMIT
#
"WORKFORCE LIMIT" "WORKFORCE LIMITS"

Usage:  workforce limit [keywords]
        workforce limit <amount | none> <keywords>

This command lets you set production limits on items. No workforce chore will
produce more than the limited amount of an item.

You can use multiple keywords to try to get the right item. Example:
> workforce limit 15 large tree

Using this command without an amount lets you search your current limits.

You can also set limits for a whole chore when turning a chore on using
"workforce <chore> <limit> [island name]".

See also: WORKFORCE, WORKFORCE KEEP
#
"WORKFORCE NEARBY"

Usage:  workforce nearby

This command shows citizens that live within 20 tiles of your current
location and could perform workforce chores. It will also indicate if they are
already working.

Artisans perform work in the shop where they live, but do not show as (working)
on this display and do not travel for other chores.

See also: WORKFORCE
#
"WORKFORCE NO-WORK" "WORKFORCE NOWORK" NO-WORK NOWORK

Usage:  workforce no-work

This command toggles workforce for the map location you're standing on.
Citizens will not perform any chores at that location.

See also: WORKFORCE
#
"WORKFORCE PRODUCTION"

The 'production' chore instructs your workforce to produce resources at some of
your buildings. If you want to use this chore, but turn off specific items, use
'workforce limit' on those items.

Common things produced by this:
 Apiary: honeycomb, beeswax
 Chicken coops: eggs, poultry
 Pasture: mutton, wool
 Pigsty: pork
 Quarry: flint, rocks, stone blocks
 Salterns: sea salt

Skilled labor also produces:
 Herb Gardens: various magic herbs
 Trapper's Post: skins, meat

See also: WORKFORCE CHORES, WORKFORCE LIMIT, SKILLED LABOR
#
"WORKFORCE PROSPECTING" "PROSPECTOR TRAINING"

With the 'prospecting' chore, your workforce will camp out on claimed mountain
tiles and slowly prospect to look for metals. This can take a long time to
finish but when it is done, any member of the empire can type 'prospect' on the
tile to instantly find out what metal it has.

You can turn on 'toggle informative' to see tiles that have been prospected by
your empire.

See also: WORKFORCE CHORES, TOGGLE INFORMATIVE
#
"WORKFORCE WHERE"

Usage:  workforce where [chore]
        workforce where here

This command will show you how many of your citizens are working on each
active workforce chore right now. It excludes citizens who have finished their
current task but haven't left the work site yet.

If you use the "here" argument, it will only check the island you're on.

See also: WORKFORCE
#
"WORKFORCE WHY"

Usage:  workforce why [chore]
        workforce why [location | here]

This command will tell you why your workforce didn't work during the last hour.

Some possible reasons include:
 no workers - Make sure there are available citizens within 20 tiles.
 over limit - You have too much of what the chore would produce.
 depleted - The location is temporarily depleted.
 no resources - You are missing the items needed to build/craft.
 already sheared - Sheep sheared too recently.
 delayed - There was a recent problem and workforce must wait to resume.
 out of city - The building must be inside a city.

If a chore is marked "delayed", that means it failed on a previous attempt and
hasn't tried again yet. Chores are delayed by a few hours when they fail.

See also: WORKFORCE
